04808nam a22007455i 9780226403533DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264035337 a10.7208/97802264035332doi  a(DE-B1597)523453  a(OCoLC)979417616  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF1623.S35bJ67 2018 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a001.0903223  aCD 11202rvk1 aJosephson-Storm, Jason A., eauthor.14aThe Myth of Disenchantment :bMagic, Modernity, and the Birth of the Human Sciences /cJason A. Josephson-Storm. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Enchanted (Post) Modernity -- tPart 1: God's Shadow -- t2. Revenge of the Magicians -- t3. The Myth of Absence -- t4. The Shadow of God -- t5. The Decline of Magic: J. G. Frazer -- t6. The Revival of Magick: Aleister Crowley -- tPart 2: The Horrors of Metaphysics -- t7. The Black Tide: Mysticism, Rationality, and the German Occult Revival -- t8. Dialectic of Darkness: The Magical Foundations of Critical Theory -- t9. The Ghosts of Metaphysics: Logical Positivism and Disenchantment -- t10. The World of Enchantment; or, Max Weber at the End of History -- tConclusion: The Myth of Modernity -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA great many theorists have argued that the defining feature of modernity is that people no longer believe in spirits, myths, or magic. Jason Ā. Josephson-Storm argues that as broad cultural history goes, this narrative is wrong, as attempts to suppress magic have failed more often than they have succeeded. Even the human sciences have been more enchanted than is commonly supposed. But that raises the question: How did a magical, spiritualist, mesmerized Europe ever convince itself that it was disenchanted? Josephson-Storm traces the history of the myth of disenchantment in the births of philosophy, anthropology, sociology, folklore, psychoanalysis, and religious studies. Ironically, the myth of mythless modernity formed at the very time that Britain, France, and Germany were in the midst of occult and spiritualist revivals. Indeed, Josephson-Storm argues, these disciplines' founding figures were not only aware of, but profoundly enmeshed in, the occult milieu; and it was specifically in response to this burgeoning culture of spirits and magic that they produced notions of a disenchanted world.   By providing a novel history of the human sciences and their connection to esotericism, The Myth of Disenchantment dispatches with most widely held accounts of modernity and its break from the premodern past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aMagicxHistory. 0aMyth. 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 0aScience and magic. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 4aMax Weber. 4adisenchantment. 4aenlightenment. 4ahistory of philosophy. 4ahistory of the social sciences. 4amagic. 4amodernity. 4amythology. 4areligion. 4areligious studies. 4ascience. 4awestern esotericism. 70(DE-601)1046587110(DE-588)4039827-4aModerne2gnd 70(DE-601)1062098090(DE-588)4043421-7aOkkultismus2gnd 70(DE-601)1062399450(DE-588)4036966-3aMagie2gnd 70(DE-601)1063383820(DE-588)4014889-0aEntmythologisierung2gnd 70(DE-601)2382855020(DE-588)4481515-3aHumanwissenschaften2gnd 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226403533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226403533.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  Univers